CMSC 14200
Discussion 3

This is another ungraded exercise for your benefit. It will take you
further in the direction of being able to build interactive games.

Please review this whole document before diving in and writing
code. You may work with another person on this task if you
like. Please stay completely away from LLMs like ChatGPT or Claude;
using any such tool would defeat the purpose of this work.

The coding task is to be able to calculate whether a disc in a field
of discs has been clicked on or not.

The "game" you create should function as follows:
    - There should be 9 circles displayed on the screen, perhaps in a grid
    - The circles should be labeled with letters (see the assets folder)
    - If a part of the screen that is not a disk is clicked, the co-ordinate
    clicked should be printed to terminal
    - If a disk is clicked, at any point in the circle, the letter of the disk 
    clicked (i.e. "A") should be printed to terminal

Possible extensions, if you finish the basic functionality:
    - Have the disk clicked change color
    - Have the disks move to new locations when one is clicked

You have been supplied with:
    - clickdiscs.py, a framework for completing this task, and
    - an assets directory containing some relevant images (look inside).

====== HOW TO RESPOND TO CLICKS

When the player/user clicks on the pygame window, a `MOUSEBUTTONDOWN`
event happens. Immediately thereafter, the position of the click is
available in the variable `event.pos`, which is a pair of integers (a
`tuple[int,int]`, in mypy terms). You will need to use `event.pos` to
determine whether or not you have clicked on a disc.

Remember that in pygame, the co-ordinate system starts as (0, 0) in the top
left corner, with x increasing to the right and y increasing down the screen.

====== DRAWING

A refresher: to draw circles, use pygame.draw.circle, as in

  pygame.draw.circle(surface, color, center, radius)

For example:

  pygame.draw.circle(self.surface, (0,0,0), (100,80), 30)

There are "letter tiles" in assets/ that you can use to add labels to
your disks. These are graphics in the .BMP image format, which is a convenient format when working with pygame.

To draw an image on a pygame surface, the commands are

  img = pygame.image.load([filename])
  surface.blit(img,[position])

For example, to draw the light blue A tile from assets on the screen,
you can write

  dir = "assets/images/letter-tiles"
  img = pygame.image.load(dir+"/letter_lightblue_uppercase_A.bmp")
  surface.blit(img,(0,0))

The `blit` method of the surface draws the given image on that
surface, with the coordinate argument as the upper-left corner of the
drawn image. ("Blit" is an old-school computer programming
abbreviation for "bit-block transfer.")

You will notice that the letter tiles, as given, are too large for
this GUI; you can scale them to different size(s) using the function
pygame.transform.scale_by, as in

  dir = "assets/images/letter-tiles"
  img = pygame.image.load(dir+"/letter_lightblue_uppercase_A.bmp")
  img = pygame.transform.scale_by(img,0.5) # the image is now half the size
  surface.blit(img,(0,0))

Enjoy the work and happy hacking!